⁸ Patricio homini] Romulus divided his people, according to their honour and dignity‚ into Patricians and Plebeians. The Patricians, i. e. patribus orti, were persons of rank and quality, bore offices of state, assisted in the administration, and took care of religious rites. The Plebeians, or commons, were to plough the ground, feed cattle, and follow trades. Every Patrician took so many of the Plebeians under his, protection, was their counsellor or adviser in difficult cases3 their advocate in judgment, and on this account was called their patron, and they his clients. On the other hand, the clients paid a great de- fercnce to their patrons, waited upon, served, and assisted them, as they were required. On some pressing occasions they furnished them with money ; but this was rarely practised3 for it was thought disho- nourable for a patron to take money of his client.—M.
